diff:1612461669:1612461669:=1,39d0%0a%3c :Category: PracticeCategory%0a%3c :Expansion: Different scales for large numbers%0a%3c :Author: david_h%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.NumbersInLanguages|NumbersInLanguages]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.abbyl|abbyl]]%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 04.02.2021 - 10:01%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c There are also some differences when talking about counting between increasing orders of magnitude. For instance, English groups these in 3s (e.g. ones, tens, hundreds is one group, thousands, ten thousands, hundred thousands is another group). This is also most evident when separating numbers when written in figures. 3,000,000 for three million.%0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, Chinese groups them in 4s in everyday usage (e.g. 1, 10, 100, 1000 is one group, 10^4, 10^5, 10^6, 10^7 is another group). This makes three million said or written more like 300,0000 in Chinese characters. (Not quite sure if other Chinese speakers use it like so, but I learned it that way.)%0a%3c %0a%3c What factors influenced such differences? How does standardization (SI) work in these cases?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
